ness and determine feature importance. SHAP (Shapley Additive Explanations) analysis further validated the significance of these features in two distinct scenarios. We analyzed two distinct scenarios in this study. In the first scenario, we utilized all five categories for classification for WGTV, achieving a maximum accuracy of 60.83% with the Random Forest (RF) model. In the second scenario, to address the issue of class imbalance, we transformed the study into a binary classification problem, which significantly improved the model’s performance, yielding the highest accuracy of 85% with the RF model. Notably, the model outputs were influenced by demographic parameters such as age and daily interactions, but their influence was mild compared to the predominant influence of socioeconomic characteristics. Analysis validated key predictors, highlighting socioeconomic factors like education and income as the most influential, while demographic factors such as age and gender had a milder effect. The findings underscore the importance of addressing socioeconomic disparities in public health efforts to boost immunization rates, offering valuable insights for policymakers to design targeted interventions and improve health outcomes. Supplementary Information The online version contains supplementary material available at 10.1186/s41043-025-01079-8. Keywords Vaccine acceptance Socioeconomic factors Public health intervention Machine learning SHAP analysis Bangladesh pmc-status-qastatus 0 pmc-status-live yes pmc-status-embargo no pmc-status-released yes pmc-prop-open-access yes pmc-prop-olf no pmc-prop-manuscript no pmc-prop-legally-suppressed no pmc-prop-has-pdf yes pmc-prop-has-supplement yes pmc-prop-pdf-only no pmc-prop-suppress-copyright no pmc-prop-is-real-version no pmc-prop-is-scanned-article no pmc-prop-preprint no pmc-prop-in-epmc yes issue-copyright-statement © BioMed Central Ltd., part of Springer Nature 2025 Introduction Nipah virus (NiV) is a highly pathogenic RNA virus belonging to the Paramyxoviridae [ 1 Pteropus 2 5 Pteropus 6 Since the first documented outbreak in 2001, Bangladesh has experienced almost annual seasonal NiV epidemics, typically occurring between December and April. As of February 2024, a total of 341 confirmed human cases and 242 deaths have been reported nationwide, the majority of cases in Bangladesh were reported in the central and northwest areas, yielding an overall case fatality rate (CFR) of approximately 73% [ 7 8 1 9 9 10 11 The COVID-19 pandemic has demonstrated how rapidly infectious diseases can escalate from initial detection to global spread. Similarly, Nipah virus (NiV) poses a significant public health threat due to its high mutation rate, enabling adaptation to new environments, cross-species transmission, immune evasion, and potential for increased human-to-human spread [ 12 7 13 14 15 16 17 18 17 19 1 20 21 1 22 22 23 24 25 26 27 Although epidemiological studies have described NiV transmission pathways, a significant gap remains in understanding how Bangladesh’s socio-economic, cultural, and behavioral factors shape public awareness and preventive practices. Addressing this gap is critical for designing effective containment strategies and preventing future public health emergencies. This study evaluates the socio-demographic, economic, and cultural determinants influencing NiV preventive behavior, particularly vaccination willingness. To achieve this, we employ interpretable machine learning models Decision Tree (DT), Random Forest (RF), and Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost) augmented with SHAP analysis to identify the most influential predictors. In parallel, evolutionary-epidemiological models are developed to simulate the impact of awareness-driven behavioral changes and public health interventions, including targeted education campaigns, vaccination programs, and healthcare system strengthening, on NiV transmission dynamics. The findings will generate evidence-based insights to guide policymakers, public health authorities, and healthcare practitioners in reducing NiV-related morbidity and mortality in Bangladesh. Machine learning (ML) has emerged as a powerful tool in public health due to its ability to process large-scale datasets with high predictive accuracy and efficiency [ 28 29 30 31 32 33 34 In parallel, numerous studies on vaccination acceptance have applied a variety of approaches, including mathematical modeling, intervention game theory, cross-sectional survey analysis, and contingent valuation (CV) surveys [ 35 35 37 38 36 39 Materials and methods Study design In response to the Nipah virus outbreak in Bangladesh, a comprehensive data collection survey was conducted under the funding of the “Internal Research Project Survey Grant by Research Projects under the Higher Training and Research Program, BUET.” The primary goal was to gain critical insights into the behavioral responses of people in various districts across Bangladesh during the epidemic. To achieve this, a cross-sectional offline survey was conducted through face-to-face interviews with individuals from seven different communities, including Rangpur, Bhola, Feni, Barisal, Narsingdi, Noakhali, and Dhaka. Additionally, an online survey was conducted to gather data from every division and over 30 districts nationwide, ensuring a mix of urban and rural perspectives for a more comprehensive understanding of the Nipah virus’s impact across different settings. The study was designed to capture the diverse effects of the epidemic on individuals from various regions and explore potential health disparities based on demographic factors like age, education, gender, and occupation. A total of 1200 completed questionnaires were collected, with interviews lasting 10–15 min per participant. The minimum required sample size was determined using Cochran’s formula, with a 95% confidence level and a 5% margin of error, based on Bangladesh’s total population (~ 176 million). This calculation yielded a required sample size of 385 respondents. Our study collected 1,200 responses, which far exceeded the minimum threshold, ensuring sufficient statistical power and representativeness. The primary survey was conducted over 17 days, from September 14 to September 30, 2024, by a team of eight interviewers (enumerators) across eight locations in Bangladesh. Trained enumerators holding undergraduate and master’s degrees from local universities engaged respondents in face-to-face interviews. These enumerators underwent a full day of training that covered comprehensive information about Nipah virus’s disease, questionnaire administration techniques, and their responsibilities. They received appropriate compensation for their contributions to the survey. All individuals aged 17 and older were eligible to participate as respondents. The participants represented a broad spectrum of social backgrounds, including differences in age, education, income, daily close contacts, and living conditions. By including a diverse range of participants, the study aimed to reflect the varied experiences and perspectives of the population. The extensive data collected enabled a detailed analysis of how the epidemic impacted different areas and demographic groups across Bangladesh. These findings will guide targeted public health interventions and policies, helping to reduce the epidemic’s effects and improve overall population health. Our proposed methodology (Fig. 1  Fig. 1 The above diagram provides a visual representation of the workflow of this study Questionnaire design Our objective was to collect comprehensive data on people’s perceptions regarding the severity of the Nipah virus, their adherence to preventive measures, cognitive valuation of vaccination, the prevalence of awareness, the behavioral impact of Nipah virus disease, and their health status. To achieve this, we meticulously designed a questionnaire that effectively captured the information necessary for our research objectives. The questionnaire was structured into five sections, each targeting different areas of inquiry. The first section focused on socioeconomic and demographic information, including age, residential area, gender, occupation, education, marital status, income, and contact details. This section aimed to understand participants’ backgrounds and the contextual factors that could influence their experiences and behaviors during the epidemic. The second section addressed health-related factors like chronic conditions like diabetes, cardiovascular or respiratory diseases, and cancer. Participants were also asked about their perspectives on preventive measures and vaccination, including what they believed to be the most critical factors in preventing the spread of the Nipah virus and the considerations influencing their decision to get vaccinated. The third section explored participants’ knowledge, attitudes, and perceptions of the Nipah virus. It included questions on symptoms, misconceptions about bats, and behaviors such as consuming bat-bitten fruits or identifying fruits bitten by bats. Participants were asked whether bats were dirty animals, blind, or essential to nature and whether they believed all bats carry the Nipah virus. The fourth section focused mainly on Nipah virus disease awareness and its behavioral impact. It examined the frequency and effectiveness of awareness campaigns, how participants learned about the Nipah virus and their opinions on the importance being informed about its risks. Additionally, participants expressed satisfaction with government efforts to raise awareness about the disease. The final section of the survey focuses on respondents’ preventive behaviors, perceptions, and willingness regarding potential Nipah virus vaccination. It captures self-reported protective measures, perceived importance of vaccination, and the key factors influencing vaccination decisions, such as effectiveness, safety, cost, and accessibility. Statistical analysis To determine the impact of demographic characteristics on an individual’s likelihood to accept vaccination, a chi-square test was performed comparing demographic data with the ‘Willingness to Get Vaccinated’ (WTGV) to check for any significant relationships. A relationship was considered statistically significant if the p Data preparation We used label encoding to convert demographic categorical features to have a numerical representation. This approach is particularly useful when the data has an inherent ordinal relationship or when dealing with high-cardinality features, where one-hot encoding can substantially increase dimensionality, making the model more complex and computationally expensive. In SHAP analysis, one-hot encoding can cause challenges in interpreting feature importance, as it splits a single categorical variable into multiple binary variables, diluting the contribution of the original feature. Label encoding, on the other hand, preserves the feature’s compactness and allows for more straightforward interpretability in SHAP analysis. We trained the machine learning models using demographic features to observe how these algorithms utilize the features in predicting vaccination willingness. This approach also provided insights into whether these features significantly influence a person’s decision. The target variable WTGV consists of five classes. However, we considered two cases in our analysis due to class imbalance, particularly for the “Not willing at all” and “Extremely willing” categories. In the first case, we trained the models using all five classes as the target variable without addressing class imbalance. We recategorized the original response scale into two binary groups for analysis to enhance interpretability. The “Not Willing” group combined individuals who were either Not Willing Slightly Willing Moderately Willing Very Willing Extremely Willing Machine learning and SHAP analysis Machine learning models, particularly tree-based algorithms, effectively identify salient features of a target variable. In this study, we utilized Random Forest (RF), Decision Tree (DT), and XGBoost classifiers to predict an individual’s willingness to get vaccinated (WTGV). RF and DT classifiers use gini impurity to determine the most relevant features for separating classes, enabling them to identify key factors influencing vaccination attitudes [ 38 40 41 42 Decision tree Decision Tree is a straightforward yet effective machine learning approach for classification and regression problems. In order to produce a tree-like structure, it recursively divides the dataset into subsets according to feature values [ 38 41 Random forest Random Forest (RF) is a robust and widely used ensemble learning algorithm, that combines multiple decision trees to improve prediction accuracy and reduce overfitting, suitable for classification [ 38 39 40 XGBoost Extreme Gradient Boosting (XGBoost), is a scalable and effective gradient-boosting method that may be used for both regression and classification tasks. Iteratively, it builds an ensemble of decision trees, each of which seeks to fix the mistakes of the one before it. XGBoost uses gradient descent to minimize a loss function at each stage and adds a regularization term to avoid overfitting. In order to create a powerful learner in terms of performance, scalability, and execution speed, it combines multiple weak learners [ 42 SHAP Relying solely on feature importance from these models can be misleading, as they may exhibit bias in specific scenarios. For instance, the Gini impurity measure used in RF and DT can favor features with high cardinality or unique categories [ 43 44 45 46 47 Evaluation metrics for classifier performance The performance of classifiers in identifying significant features influencing the decision of willingness to get vaccinated (WTGV) was evaluated using several key metrics, including accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, and precision. 