hly willing to vaccinate (VW and EW categories), compared to only about 36% of men showing similar enthusiasm. Regarding marital status, single individuals are notably more willing to get vaccinated than their married counterparts. Educational attainment also plays a significant role, with more educated individuals demonstrating a considerably higher willingness to vaccinate than those with lower education levels, as shown in Fig. 2 2 Analysis using machine learning Table 4  Table 4 Prediction result of RF, DT, and XGBoost Case-I Algorithms Accuracy Precision Recall F1 Score Random Forest 60.83% 72.91% 47.22% 48.58% Decision Tree 59.58% 53.47% 49.03% 49.84% XGBoost 55.41% 52.85% 50.10% 51.10% Case-II Algorithms Accuracy Precision Recall F1 Score Random Forest 85.00% 82.23% 77.05% 79.04% Decision Tree 84.17% 79.66% 79.04% 79.34% XGBoost 83.75% 78.91% 79.78% 79.33% Figure 3  Fig. 3 Feature importance analysis across different machine learning models. This figure illustrates the feature importance rankings obtained from three machine learning models- Random Forest ( a-i b-i a-ii b-ii a-iii b-iii Case-I Case-II The findings highlight that educational qualifications, income, and occupation are key determinants of vaccination willingness. Interestingly, demographic factors such as area of residence, marital status, and gender play a relatively minor role according to these machine-learning models. This indicates that socio-economic attributes, rather than basic demographics, are more critical in predicting an individual’s likelihood of accepting vaccination. SHAP analysis The summary plot from the SHAP analysis for the trained models is presented in Fig. 4 5  Fig. 4 SHAP value analysis of feature importance across machine learning models. This figure illustrates a detailed SHAP (SHapley Additive exPlanations) value analysis of feature importance across three machine learning models- Random Forest( a-i b-i a-ii b-ii a-iii b-iii Case-I Case-II  Fig. 5 Beeswarm plot of SHAP values for correct predictions using three machine learning models. This figure showcases the Beeswarm plots of SHAP values (impact on model output) for accurate projections across three machine learning models: Random Forest( a-i b-i a-ii b-ii a-iii b-iii Case-I Case-II The SHAP values also highlight “family monthly income” as the second most crucial contributor after “max educational qualification” in the Random Forest (RF) model. The analysis reveals that higher family incomes positively influence correct predictions, reinforcing that wealthier individuals are more inclined to vaccinate. However, lower income levels demonstrate mixed contributions, with some leading to positive impacts on predictions while others result in negative influences. This variability underscores that income can be a nuanced predictor depending on additional context within the data. In Decision Tree (DT) models, the beeswarm plots reflect similar findings, with “family monthly income” consistently ranking as the third most influential feature. The similarity between RF and DT results suggests robust patterns across different tree-based models regarding income’s role in vaccination prediction. Conversely, features like “gender,” “marital status,” and “family size” are shown to be less impactful across all models in both cases, indicating minimal influence on the predictions. This aligns with earlier findings where the models also ranked these attributes low in feature importance. Interestingly, in the Decision Tree and XGBoost models, “age” and “average daily interaction” exhibit notable contributions, contrasting with their lower significance in the RF model. In these models, “age” and daily interaction patterns influence predictions more prominently, indicating that demographic and social behavior factors may be more relevant in these specific algorithms. On the other hand, RF continues to downplay their importance, suggesting model-specific differences in feature sensitivity. Overall, the SHAP analysis and beeswarm plots provide comprehensive evidence that socioeconomic factors, especially educational qualification, and income, are the most decisive in predicting vaccination willingness. While demographic factors like age and daily interactions play a role in specific models, they are generally less critical across all cases. The consistency between feature importance rankings and SHAP analyses highlights the reliability of these findings, emphasizing that understanding vaccination behavior requires focusing on socioeconomic disparities more than basic demographic distinctions. Discussion The findings from the socio-demographic analysis and machine learning models provide critical insights into the factors influencing WTGV, which can be utilized to inform and enhance public health policymaking. Higher educational qualifications, family income, and smaller family size were strongly associated with a greater inclination toward vaccination, suggesting that socioeconomic status plays a pivotal role in vaccination acceptance. These patterns align with recent multi-country and regional syntheses, which show that education and economic security underpin vaccine confidence and uptake in low- and middle-income settings, including those in South Asia [ 48 49 49 50 and The machine learning analysis offered a more nuanced understanding of the relative importance of these factors, mainly agreeing with the classical statistical analysis. Across multiple algorithms, “MaxEducationQualification” consistently emerged as the most critical predictor of vaccination willingness, which is also shown in a study across the United States for COVID-19 vaccination as one of six main factors [ 51 52 53 54 Our findings mainly suggest that public health strategies should prioritize education-first messaging by delivering accurate information about vaccination in plain language, busting local myths through trusted messengers or celebrities, complemented with visual tools and community dialogues to engage groups with lower educational attainment. Reducing economic barriers is equally essential, which can be achieved by providing free or subsidized vaccines, deploying mobile clinics near workplaces and markets, and offering modest transport or wage-loss compensation to offset income-related constraints. Engagement approaches should also be tailored to the place in rural settings, leveraging local leaders and in-person forums can build trust, while in urban contexts, digital platforms and workplace-based campaigns may be more effective. Given the observed gender differences, male-targeted outreach should emphasize the benefits of vaccination in safeguarding family well-being and income stability while directly addressing risk perceptions. The higher willingness observed among females emphasizes that they should be given more autonomy in health-related decision-making for the family. Limitations and future directions This study elucidates significant insights regarding the socioeconomic responses to Nipah virus vaccination in Bangladesh; however, it is imperative to acknowledge several limitations. Firstly, the data were derived from a relatively limited cohort of the national population, which may constrain the generalizability of the findings. Despite efforts to capture a diverse array of responses, a predominant portion of the respondents were students (54.5%), skewing the sample toward a younger demographic and potentially affecting the validity of the conclusions. Secondly, the reliance on self-reported data poses inherent challenges such as recall bias, social desirability bias, and potential misrepresentation of sensitive attitudes toward vaccination. Furthermore, while the analysis primarily concentrated on socioeconomic and demographic predictors of willingness to vaccinate against the Nipah virus (WTGV), it did not take into account other significant variables that could influence vaccination attitudes, including cultural beliefs, exposure to misinformation regarding vaccines, trust in health authorities, and perceptions of vaccine safety and efficacy. The omission of these variables could limit the explanatory power necessary for a comprehensive understanding of vaccine hesitancy. Additionally, although the application of machine learning techniques and SHAP analysis yielded valuable insights, the efficacy of these models is contingent upon the quality, completeness, and representativeness of the input data utilized. To address these limitations, future research should aim to conduct more extensive investigations that monitor shifts in public attitudes toward vaccination throughout different phases of an outbreak and post-outbreak scenarios. Expanding the survey scope to encompass a larger, nationally representative sample, in conjunction with qualitative interviews, could facilitate a more nuanced comprehension of the motivations and barriers to vaccination. Moreover, integrating behavioral, cultural, and psychosocial variables alongside demographic factors would enhance predictive modeling and inform targeted interventions. Conclusion Our study demonstrates that willingness to vaccinate (WTGV) against the Nipah virus in Bangladesh is determined by a complex interplay of socio-demographic and socioeconomic factors. Education and family income emerged as the most influential predictors, consistently ranked highest across Decision Tree, Random Forest, and XGBoost models. At the same time, SHAP analysis further validated that lower education and income levels were associated with reduced vaccination willingness. Statistical analyses also revealed significant associations ( p Supplementary Information Below is the link to the electronic supplementary material.  Supplementary Material 1 Publisher’s note Springer Nature remains neutral with regard to jurisdictional claims in published maps and institutional affiliations. Acknowledgements The authors would like to thank the anonymous reviewers for 